I found a solution by myself.

First I added a condition to the Message Task. So the lines are filtered. Only lines that indicate an error are printed out.

Second I replaced the CreateProperty Task. I use a PropertyGroup now to create a property that contains all lines (not exactly what I wanted initially, but it works for me together with the next point).

And third I modified the error condition. I check if in the whole text an error occurred.

    &lt;Target Name=&quot;CheckLog&quot;&gt;
		&lt;PropertyGroup&gt;
			&lt;ErrorText&gt;ERR&lt;/ErrorText&gt;
		&lt;/PropertyGroup&gt;
		
		&lt;ReadLinesFromFile File=&quot;execution.log&quot; &gt;
			&lt;Output TaskParameter=&quot;Lines&quot; ItemName=&quot;FileContents&quot; /&gt;
		&lt;/ReadLinesFromFile&gt;
		
		&lt;Message Text=&quot;%(FileContents.Identity)&quot; Condition=&quot;$([System.String]::Copy(&#39;%(FileContents.Identity)&#39;).StartsWith($(ErrorText)))&quot; /&gt;
		
        &lt;PropertyGroup&gt;
            &lt;AllLines&gt;@(FileContents)&lt;/AllLines&gt;
        &lt;/PropertyGroup&gt;
        &lt;Error Condition=&quot;$(AllLines.Contains($(ErrorText)))&quot; Text=&quot;Execution returned with an error.&quot; /&gt;
    &lt;/Target&gt;

Maybe even more elegant: Using an Error Task, only:

    &lt;Target Name=&quot;CheckLog&quot;&gt;
        &lt;PropertyGroup&gt;
            &lt;ErrorText&gt;ERR&lt;/ErrorText&gt;
